### <a id="configure-app-manifest"></a> Configure SSO Properties with the App Manifest

To register your app, you can configure the SSO service instance you want to bind your app to 
and configure the SSO configuration properties in your app manifest. 
With this method you do not need to manually bind your app to the service instance after you deploy your app. 
The SSO service reads its configuration properties from environment variables
that are set in the apps that use it.

<p class="note"><strong>Note:</strong> These configurations are only applied at
	the time of the initial service bind. If you run <code>cf push</code> again, the app does
	not update the configurations. You can update the configurations through the SSO Developer Dashboard.</p>

The snippet below shows how to register your app with a SSO service instance
and how to configure the `GRANT_TYPE` and `SSO_IDENTITY_PROVIDERS` SSO properties in your manifest.

```
---
applications:
  - name: my-example-app
    services:
    - my-sso-sample-instance
    env:
      GRANT_TYPE: implicit
      SSO_IDENTITY_PROVIDERS: uaa, sample-identity-provider
```

For examples of bootstrapping SSO properties, see the `manifest.yml` files in the 
[identity-sample-apps](https://github.com/pivotal-cf/identity-sample-apps) GitHub repository.

